    "However, in contrast to Sect. 2.1.1, the following methods are not equally applicable to forward and inverse problems.",
    "Thus, the prediction of the solution û, the PDE coefficients λ, and the non-linear operator N are treated separately.",
    "Differential equation solving with neural networksThe concept of solving PDEsfoot_8 was first proposed in the 1990s [8][9][10], but was recently popularized by the so-called physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) [228] (see [229][230][231] for recent review articles and SciANN [232], SimNet [233], DeepXDE [234] for libraries).To illustrate the idea and variations of PINNs, we will consider the differential equation of a static elastic bard dx E A du dx + p = 0, x ∈.",
    "(25)Here, the operator N is given by the left-hand side of the equation, the solution u(x) is the axial displacement, and the spatially varying coefficients λ(x) are given by the crosssectional properties E A(x) and the distributed load p(x).Additionally, boundary conditions are specified, which can be in terms of Dirichlet (on D) or Neumann boundary conditions (on N):u(x) = g(x), x ∈ D, (26) E A(x) du(x) dx = f (x), x ∈ N. (27) Physics-informed neural networksPINNs [228] approximate either the solution u(x), the coefficients λ(x), or both with FC-NNs.û(x) = F F N N (x; θ u) (28) λ(x) = I F N N (x; θ λ) (29)Instead of training the network with labeled data as in Eq.",
